article.headline: Jefferson, Martin, Kidd feast on Celtics

images.name: Martin Kenyon 040125 inline 195x262
images.caption: Kenyon Martin, who had a double-double, and the Nets broke away from a five-game losing streak.

article.linkText: Nets knock off Celtics to halt slide
article.story:
EAST RUTHERFORD, N.J. (AP) -- With the work of moving the franchise to Brooklyn, N.Y., now beginning despite a small group of protests, the New Jersey Nets finally got back to playing well again. Richard Jefferson scored 25 points and the Nets ended their longest losing streak since Jason Kidd joined the team more than two years ago with a 110-91 win over the Boston Celtics on Sunday before a near sellout crowd of 17,533. "It's great for New Jersey to come out and still support us," Kidd said after the Nets' first home game since the sale of the team was announced. "We have nothing to do with the business side. All we can do is go out there and play good basketball. We tried to do that this afternoon. The crowd was great." Kenyon Martin added 20 points and 15 rebounds and Kidd had 10 points, 11 assists and nine rebounds to help the two-time defending Eastern Conference champions snap a five-game slide. Nets coach Byron Scott wasn't around for the final 14 minutes. He was ejected late in the third quarter by referee Luis Grillo for saying something that earned a one-technical ejection. "I guess I said enough," Scott said. "I don't think I did, but what the heck." Assistant coach Lawrence Frank, who has been rumored to be Scott's successor if the Nets falter this season, finished as New Jersey beat the Celtics for the 12th time in 13 games, including the playoffs. Ricky Davis had 26 points to lead the Celtics, who had a two-game winning streak snapped. "I guess it is fair to say they do have our number," said a foul-plagued Paul Pierce, who had 13 points on 3-of-15 shooting from the field. "Right now, they do have a better team than us." Scott had to be happy with what he saw in the opening three quarters, even though the Nets had 29 turnovers. Besides getting big games from his big three, Scott also got some good production from Rodney Rogers and Lucious Harris off his much maligned bench. New Jersey also stepped up its defense, holding the Celtics to 35.6 percent shooting from the field. About 30 fans protested the sale and move outside the arena before the game, but it was hard to tell whether any of the fans were upset during the game. It seemed no one booed when the team was introduced before tipoff. "It was a good crowd," said Martin, who was 9-of-12 from the field. "Let's hope all the fans get in all the games while they can. It's not going to happen for another two or three years anyway. We're still here and we're going to play for them." The Nets grabbed the lead for good with an 11-2 spurt late in the first quarter. Kidd ignited the run with a 3-pointer, Rogers had a layup and two free throws and backup center Aaron Williams had two free throws and an assist on an alley-oop by Martin. "We gave them life from the start and that hurt us," Davis said. "You can't give any ballclub life, or a team in first place confidence, whether they are losing or winning." After Boston cut the lead to six on a free throw by Chris Mihm in the second quarter, Harris helped stretch the halftime lead to 17 by scoring 12 second-quarter points. Jefferson gave the fans something to laugh about in the third quarter, hitting a 30-foot, 3-pointer at the buzzer. He was 9-of-14 from the field.

Game notes
The Celtics are 13-17 vs. the Eastern Conference and 9-7 against the Western Conference, which is considered tougher. ... The Nets are 2-0 against the Celtics this season. ... The blowout came just two days after the Nets were beaten 85-64 in Miami. ... Harris also picked up a technical for elbowing Pierce seconds after Scott was ejected. ... New Jersey shot 50 percent from the field and outrebounded Boston 55-32.
